availability.p: This resource has been designed for free consultation in association with the Sloane Consortium of UK national institutions which hold the original manuscript catalogue documents and related collections of Sir Hans Sloane. All content is reproducible as long as the source is indicated by referencing the publication and the name of the institutional owner of the original catalogue manuscript -- in this case The British Museum.

notesStmt.note: An article outlining the research considerations and decision making processes guiding the marking up of the Sloane collection catalogues in the framework of the Enlightenment Architectures project can be found at Ortolja-Baird, A., Pickering, V., Nyhan, J., Sloan, K. and Fleming, M., 2019. ‘Digital Humanities in the Memory Institution: The Challenges of Encoding Sir Hans Sloane’s Early Modern Catalogues of His Collections.’ Open Library of Humanities, 5(1), p.44. DOI: http://doi.org/10.16995/olh.409 The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. These transcriptions were then fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team that is also responsible for the complete TEI markup of the transcriptions.

msIdentifier.msName: Catalogue of 'Miscellanies, Antiquities, Seals, Pictures, Mathematical Instruments, Agate handles, Agate Cups, Bottles, Spoons'

msItem.colophon: ’Miscellanies’ is a bound manuscript volume containing individual separate catalogues titled 'Miscellanies'; ‘Antiquities’; ‘Seals’; 'Pictures'; 'Mathematical Instruments'; 'Agate Handles' and 'Agate Cups, Bottles, Spoons'. It also includes Indices to the 'Seals' and to the 'Mathematical Instruments'. These catalogues contain numbered entries that list and describe the huge array of these categories of objects collected by Sir Hans Sloane (1660-1753) between the 1680s and the 1750s. In total there are 329 folios that have been bound and numbered as such at a later date, all of which contain manuscript markings on their rectos and 88 of which contain manuscript marking on their versos, plus a few tipped in slips, some of which contain manuscript markings on both their rectos and their versos. Each individual catalogue begins at number one. The folio numbers were added by a modern hand but have been transcribed so that they can be easily matched with the file names of the digital images of the pages (eg. EPF108491001, EPF108491002, EPF108491003, EPF108491003v: the last three numbers are the folio numbers). Sloane did not number the pages of the catalogues himself except for the 'Seals' which were paginated using Roman numerals. These are noted in the transcriptions. 'Miscellanies' contains 2107 numbered entries on fols. 2-152 (numbers 2108-2111 on fol. 27v are post-Sloane additions to the British Museum). 'Antiquities' contains 1129 numbered entries on fols. 153-205 (post-Sloane additions are added on versos only of fols. 178v-198v). 'Seals' includes impressions of them and contains 268 entries on fols. 206-231. The 'Index inSigilla, Sigillorum, Impressiones' is on fols. 232-236v. The references in the Index are to underlined words in the catalogue and to the Roman numeral page references. 'Pictures' includes drawings and contains 471 entries on fols. 237-271 (two post-Sloane additions are on fol. 271). 'Mathematical Instruments' contains 55 entries on fols. 272-277 (one post-Sloane entry is on fol. 277). The 'Index to the Mathematical Instruments' is on fols. 278-281 and the references are to the catalogue numbers. 'Agate handles' contains 239 entries on fols. 283-303. 'Agate cups bottles spoons' contains 303 entries on fols. 304-329. The entries for 'Miscellanies' and 'Antiquities' are on the rectos for the first approximately 66 percent of the catalogues and then continue on the versos from the beginning of the catalogues. The lists for the other individual catalogues within this volume appear consistently on the recto sides of the pages with additions and notes added on numerous occasions to the preceding (and therefore facing) verso. These are usually connected to an entry by the scribe’s use of an asterisk or ‘libra ponda’ (hashtag) symbol. Hans Sloane resided in Bloomsbury Square, London and later at Chelsea Manor House. His collecting activities spanned the early modern and Enlightenment periods and are global in scope. A physician and President of the Royal Society, he was an influential figure in the intellectual developments of his time both in England and Europe. At his death his will stipulated that his collections should be bought by the State for the purposes of creating a public Museum, thereby creating the British Museum in 1753. Since that time, Sloane’s collections have been divided between the British Museum, The British Library and the Natural History Museum (London), which institutions still retain most of his collections and catalogues. The provenance of these manuscript catalogues is therefore direct and accountable. Sloane did not publish these catalogues of his collection in his lifetime, and these digital scholarly editions created by the Enlightenment Architectures project are the first ever publications of any of these catalogues. They are mostly in Sloane's hand but various amanuenses (including Cromwell Mortimer c.1693-1752) and James Empson (d. 1765)), assisted at various times; the default hand is Sloane's and although non-Sloane hands are noted in the markup of the transcriptions, these hands are not identified in the markup. A helpful recent publication concerning the identification of hands in Sloane’s Library catalogues is: A. Blakeway, ‘The library catalogues of Sir Hans Sloane: their authors, organisation, and functions’, Electronic British Library Journal (2011), pp. 1-49. DOI: https://www.bl.uk/eblj/2011articles/pdf/ebljarticle162011.pdf There are additional notes in the catalogues made by later British Museum curators, notably those initialled E.H. (Edward Hawkins (1780-1867)) and A.W.F. (Augustus Wollaston Franks (1826-1897)). It is estimated that Sloane made at least 50 catalogues of the various parts of his collection, including his Natural History collections and Library. Further information and further reading about his collections and catalogues can be found on the Reconstructing Sloane website https://reconstructingsloane.org/ and on the websites of the institutions he founded and which have contributed to this research project: The British Museum, The British Library, The Natural History Museum (London) and those in which he was closely involved, such as The Royal Society.

front.p:
Sloane, who was born in 1660 at Killyleagh, Co. Down, came
to London in 1679 to study medicine. He continued his education
at Paris and Montpelier, and received the degree of Doctor of
Medicine from the University of Orange in 1683.

In 1687 he went to Jamaica as physician to the Duke of Albemarle,
and stayed there fifteen months, studying natural history and
collecting specimens. In 1689 he settled in Bloomsbury Square and
built up a large practice: Queen Anne was among his patients. He
was Secretary of the Royal Society, 1693-1712, and President 1719-41:
in 1694 he was placed in charge of Christ's Hospital, holding this
appointment until 1730.

On retiring from practice in 1741, he settled at the Manor House,
Chelsea, where he died on 11 Jan. 1753 and was buried in Chelsea
churchyard. His taste for books and natural history is commemorated
by Pope and Young.

He bequeathed his collections to the nation for the sum of
£20,000, far below their value, to be paid to his family. Though
among his printed books medicine and natural history are strongly
represented, there are many works on other subjects; in fact for
the first half century of the existence of the Museum, Sloane's
books formed the bulk of the collection of printed material, while
his manuscripts, containing letters and notes by most of the promi-
nent physicians of the century preceding his death, are one of the
main sources of medical history from the time of Charles II to that
of George II.

N. B. The Indexes to the Seals and Mathematical Instruments are in this Volume at the end of the respective Catalogues: and the Indexes to the rest of this Volume are bound up in a separate Volume in the same Order as they occur in this.

# De la Province de Chensi On tire d'un grand nombre de carrieres
une espéce de pierre molle, ou de minéral
appellé Hiung Hoang, dont on fait des
vases en sculpture, & que les medecins
regardent commé un souverain remede
contre toutes fortes de Venins, contre
les fievres malignes, & contre les chaleurs
contagieuses de la canicule. Its font
tremper ce minéral dans le vin avant
que des'en servir. It est de couleur
rouge tirant sur le jaune, & marqueté
de petits points noirs: il ressemble
assez a du crayon. Vid. du Halde
Descript. de l'Empiree de la chine. tom
1st. page. 208.

Explanation of the weights
The german Essay masters try the smallest
✓ 199 wt. that will turn their Scales without
having any regard to any real weight,
this they call an half Drachm. the weight
which just turns these Scales is nearly 1/16 gr.
from this arbitrary 1/2 Z. by doubling trebbling &c.
they form arbitrary small weights up to one
which in proportion answers to an Hund red wt.
the Centenarium or Centner. the subdivisions
are as follow & are thus markt on id wt.
C. centner -100. tt
XXIV. 2. Doz. or 24. tt.
XII 1. Doz. 12.
VI. 1/2 Doz. 6.
III. 1/4. Doz. 3.
II 1/6. Doz. 2.
I 1/12. Doz. 1. tt.

p.add:
#They have a fashion to cut holes in the
lips of the Boys when they are young
close to their Chin: which they keep
open wt. little pegs till they are 14 or 15 years
old, then they wear Beards in them, made
of Turtle or Tortoise shell in the form
you see in the Margin) The little notch
at the upper end they put in thro' the Lip
where it remains between the teeth & the Lip
the under part hangs down over their 8.
Chin. This they commonly wear all Day, & when
they sleep they take it out. Dampiers Voy.
Vol. 1. p. 32.

p.add:
Vppon Evaporation, it first lets fall
a few grains of a red Earth, like that in
Chalybeate Waters.
Afterward a very white , Light Earth
of this Earth there is about a
Drachm & Two Scruples in a Gallon
of ye Water.
In this Earth is conteined a small
quantity of Salt of a toxiciall Tast.
And ye Earth beeing put into fair
water, makes it a kind of Lie.
Spirit of Nitre poured upon this
Earth, causeth a vehement effervescence
And so likewise after ye salt is ex
tracted out of it.
The salt cannot well be exhi-
bited in its own forma without a
Gallon or two of ye Water.

Experiments made with the
German Water sent me by his Grace
the Duke of Newcastle. It alters not with Spirit of Harts
Horne. Nor I suppose with any Vrinous
Spirit.
An Infusion of Quick Lime, poured
on it, produceth a White cloud, which va
nish after a short time.
Spirit of Nitre produceth a white
cloud which setleth to the bottome of
the Water, yet so as to be perma-
nent in ye manner of a Cloud.
The powder of a Deyers Gall, makes
it opacous & white , like milk or milk
Tea.
And in y e space of an hour or two,
it late fall a White setling like white
flower, & grows greenish at ye top.

div3.p:
A Mummy found in its coffin among the ancient Catacombs, about three leages from Cairo in ye Year
1721. The body remains intire wrapt up in
its band g ages, but without any appearance of
hieroglyphics upon it. It was brought in the
Coffin from Egypt by the Colonel, but is since
deposited in a mohogany case wt a glass lid set
in a frame. Lenght of the body 5 feet 1 inch
breadth cross the shoulders 1 foot 4 1/4 inches.

The coffin which contained the Mummy made
of sycamore Wood in the form of the Corps &
beautifully adorned all round wt hieroglyphics.
it is now placed upright in a Mohogany case
wt glass sides that ye whole may be exposed
to view. Height of the coffin w t the Base
that supports it 6 feet 6 inches. a
particular explication of the Hieroglyphics
painted on this coffin has been published
by Mr Alexander Gordon.

The Hieroglyphics of the Coffin, painted
upon a canvass cloth, strained. Height of ye
canvass 7 feet 10 1/2 inches. breadth

Isis sitting, with Orus in her lap and a
calathus or basket on her head; in
which was probably the moons orb, inclosed
on each side with the horns of an ox, her
usual attribute; but that is now broken
off, She has a late on her forehead, and long
hair, which falls down her back behind, and
from each shoulder before, to her breasts.
Her right hand is placed under her left
breast, and with the other she supports her
infant son. She has bracelets on her arms;
and the lower part of her body from the wast
to her ancles is cloathed with a linen gar=
ment like that of Osiris. The head of Orus
is shaved, except on large lock of hair,
which remaining on the right side rests on
that shoulder: He has also a lote on his
forehead and his body is naked. Height 7 Inches
on a Wooden pedl.

The Gift of Pitt Lethieullier Esqr

A Mummy in its sycamore Coffin brought
from Egypt by the donor. The Hieroglyphics
are yet very plain on the breast and Legs, as
likewise on two separate covers, one for the face
and the other for the feet, the coffin is fashioned
to the shape of the corps, with the face and covering
on the Head, cut in relief upon the upper part of
the Lid. The remainder of which seems to have been
ornamented wt hieroglyphics painted upon it, like
those on the coffin above described in Number 2
of Colonel Lethieullier's. But Time has in a great
measure defaced them, except on the Breast and
belly, where they are still very visible. Len n ght
of the Body 5 feet 4 inches. breadth, cross the
shoulders 1 foot 3 inches, Lenght of the Coffin
5 feet 10 inches.

p.add:
Severall pieces of broken pateræ & Urns
some of Red earth & some of Black earth
wch have been washt by the sea: they
were pickt up close under the sandy cliff
at Reculver, by Cr: Mortimer anno. 1730.
-the cliff was at that time considerably wash.
ed away within ye memory of some old people
who remember'd it 40 or 50. feet farther into
ye sea, they had now staked & hurdled the beach
for a quarter of a mile or more, wch prevents
ones finding coins or such small things as can
fall thro' ye faggots: there were considerable
pieces of stone wall washt down in to ye sea
some of them 2 yards thick & high & 3 or 4 long
the Inhabitants called them part of ye church yard
wall, but the whole church yard is a direct
Square & Even, ten or twenty feet higher than
ye ground round about & on ye 3 sides next ye
land surrounded with ye foundation of an old
Roman wall, wch seems to have been a fort
or castle.

div3.p:
A peice of a black Urn found by ye same
lying in y e street near ye corner of ye garden
wall of ye Friars at Canterbury.

p.add:
a peice of a Patera of read earth , finely glazed
& beautifully adorned with flourishes & Ivy. leaves, it
was dug up in street in Canterbury in laying
ye foundation of an house about five feet deep; they
found severall Roman bricks & a thick wall wch
runs under ground cross ye street: it was given to
C. Mortimer by Dr. Gray a physician there.

div3.p:
Part of a Roman brick , with furrows on one
side of it, of this sort are all ye Key bricks of ye arches
over ye loop- holes of ye Roman pharos in Dover
castle: this seems to have been a singular contrivance
to let in ye sand & stones mixt with ye mortar while
liquid, wch would insinuate itself, & ye Stones would
lodge in these furrows & keep ye bricks at a proper
distance spreading at top to form an arch. The
pharos hath been pulled, or tumbled half down
& a church now without a roof hath been built
adjoining to it, to wch it served as a Steep le
& Bellferry, till Sr. George Rook obtain'd bare
to remove ye Bells to Hyth: it hath been a great
dispute among antiquarians whether this, or some
Stones called by ye Natives ye Devills bit upon an
hill South West of the castle on ye other side of ye town
was ye Roman Watch tower: I think ye situation
declares yt this tower wch stands higher & upon ye
point of a precipice wch juts considerably more
into ye sea & may be seen beyond ye point at Folk
stone [ Lapis Tituli ] must have been the pharos, &
not ye Devill's bit wch Stands on an high hill indeed
but at ye bottom of a Bay, wch forms ye Harbour
of Dover, & truly ye Remains of those Stones seem
only to have been ye bottom of a pillar,wch
might serve as a Land mark in ye Day time; or as
a guide for ships to go into this haven by.

Pieces of Roman brick from Richborough cas-
tle [ Rutupiæ ] near Sandwich. by ye Same. An. 1730.

Part of a patera found on St. Peters sand
at ye mouth of ye River Blackwater wch runs by
Maldon; I found here at low water severall ragged
pieces of freestone , of wch there is none naturally
on this shoar, & a great many pieces of Roman
brick: upon ye Sea wall stands an old Roman building
now a barn, but commonly called St. Peters chapple
# a great [farmer's] house

near ye S W corner of the fine variegated pave-

English in Robert Bruces reign & that of Ed. 2. of England

p.add:
this seems to have been ye place, where stood the O-
thona of ye Romans or Ithanchester of ye Saxons
vid. Gibsons Cambden p. 411. Lond. 1722. in fol.
The fisher-men told me they often drudge up pieces
of broken Earthen ware & sometimes tho' rarely
Copper or Brass money. On ye opposite side of ye River
lies Mersey Island a fine high spot of ground, &
in the # hall yard adjoining to ye Church yard of
West - Mersey Parish is a fine ancient Mosaick
pavement where of

div3.p:
are some Tessulæ ; in the Hall yard it his
but a foot under ground, I traced it to ye Church
yard pailes & had an hole dug in ye Church Yard
about 4. feet deep at about 10. feet distance
from y e stile & there found a continuation of ye
same pavement, ye course of ye Tessulæ being
paralell to those in ye Hall Yard & on ye same
levell; they lay 20. degrees to ye North Eastward of
ye North #. The minister & Sexton told me yt the
whole church yard was paved at ye same depth
& yt most of ye coffins stand on these pavements
wch are East; & SE of ye church large tyles 14.
inches square, in ye Chancell red tessulæ 1 1/2 square
& West of ye church small tyles 2 or 3 inches square
& yt once two Brass coins were found here, but I
could not learn whose they were, they being lost
again: yt the tessulæ in the Chancell seem to form
ye Rays of some large stars. The Mosaick work in
ye Hall yard forms only Squares, Wreaths & a border
of Ivy leaves: ye colours are white , Black , blew , red
& yellow , disposed in shades being black white outermost
then blew & terminating in black white & in other parts of white Red
it outermost then yellow & ending in white Red .
Sept. 1730.

of wch is 6 Balls, wth an Earls Coronet. Pewter, round.

Ditant concordes Numina nuptos. Round an emblematical
marriage. Ceremony. Wedding- piece , viz: the view of a Palace, in ye midst of which
is an Altar, two hands join'd, two Rings running thro' two
hearts &c. ye mark at bottom P. Hell. Pewter round.

Ceres offering her gifts to a Hero seated on a Throne, with
this Motto: Scilicet hune vivus Cereris quoque partus adorat ,
Cumque sorore olim Cynthius ipse colet. Pewter, round.
(XX.
A figure of St. Andrew , holding his Cross. Lead. oval.
An antique Head impress'd on Lead. Small. Oval.

A female head. Small. round. Lead.
Another female head. small, oval. Lead.

Pallas sitting, armed. Lead, small, oval.
Hercules standing, leaning on his Club, wth a female figure
standing by him &c. Lead, small, oval.

A Lyon Rampant. Lead, small, oval.
A Lyon sitting, holding a Flag. Lead, oval. a little bigger?
A Boar running, wth a Dart in its shoulder? Lead, small, oval.

A Coat of Arms , a Chevron, bearing 3 Stars. Lead, small. oval.
Another , 3 birds, 2 & 1. parted by a Chevron. above the Crest
a Grey hound sitting. Lead, small, oval.

Honi soit qui mal y ponse. round the Arms of a Duke.
The Arms of ye Marquis of Lothian? Both Lead small, oval.

The Coat of Arms of a marquis an Earl.
A Cypher , wth an Earl's Coronet.
A Cypher , wth a wreath round it. } Lead, small, oval.

An altar piece , in wch. a Dove descending thro' flames:
above wch a Dome wth a Cross on it: at each the Corners
Angels, one holding a Crown, the other a Scepter.
Lead, large, oval, boldly raised.

A figure of Time , lifting up a naked figure &c, and
this motto in the field: Veritas filia temporis.
and round the Edges in a Circle this Inscription:
Abstrusam Tenebris Tempus meeducit in auras. H. G 1570.
Lead, round, large.

Jupiter tonans fulminating a number of Mankind &c.
with this Motto: Discite justitiam morviti.
Lead, round. Less.
XXI.

A Sensual Woman sitting, tempted by several Sins
in grotesque figures of Monks &c: the one of which is
looking out of the trunk of a Tree. Lead. square. large.

A Landskip , in wch is a Woman drawing Water
out of a Well, another giving drink in a Pitcher
to a man &c. The Story of Rebecca ?
Lead, round, large.
The ascension of our Saviour. Lead. oval, small.

A Ploughman sitting melancholy on a broken
Plough. Lead, round, small.

Two naked Figures (Justice & Peace) recumbent and
embracing, wth several other ornaments, over wch this
Motto: Justisia et Pax. and round the border:
Justitia et Pax osculataæ sunt, misericordia et veritas
obviaverunt Sibi. Lead, round, very large, well raised.

A naked Boys , standing, and holding a Spear: with
a Serpent at his feet. Brass, oblong square, well raised.

A naked Boy riding on a Seahorse in sea , wch a vessel
pouring out water &c. Copper, oblong Square, well raised.

A Groupe of figures, chiefly naked boys playing, the
fig. in ye middle holding a large handled Cup.
Lead. round. large.

A Landskip with figures pursuing rural Diversions ,
as Fishing, Hawking, Fowling &c. Lead. round. pretty
large.

A Bishop sitting , wth Keys in the right, & a book in ye. left
hand. Cut in Box, Basso relievo. Round , wth four handles
or Loops.
(XXII.

The Busto of K. Henry VIII. relief on Silver gilt, round.
It seems to have been the Cover of a Box.

Another of Do. smaller, an impression i o n wax, on a board.
an? already enter'd N o. 59?
A last of the preceding in Chalk.

A hunting piece done in a circular manner, the middle
vacant. Lead, emboss'd, round.
Six heads , three & three, an impression in Chalk. oval.

A fleet of Ships before a City, with naval Ornaments
round the Border. an impression in brown Clay.

Another smaller Do. with this Inscription:
Service done against six Ships, July. 31 & aug:1. 16 7 50.

A King in his regalia, holding a prince in one hand,
the other hand on an altar: with several figures standing
on the other side of ye altar, the principal of which has his
hand on it. (a Treaty of Peace wth the Suiss Cantons.) with
this Inscription round the border:
Nulla dies sub me natoque hæc fædera rumpet.
& this at bottom: Fædere Helvetico instaurato.
An impression on Chalk. round.

A naked Boy ( Cupid ) shooting an ar row out of a Bow.
Lead, an oblong Square.

A Bust, the head wreath'd, in the antique manner.
Lead, well raised, oval, small.

The Judgment of Paris? viz: a naked figure of a man
sitting, and reaching an apple to one of three female figures,
who has a Child standing by her, and Mercury behind ye man.
Lead, well raised, small, transverse, oval.

Card 17. contains 24 Casts or Chasings of Medals. On Pewter silver'd.
all of the same size, in the following Order:
(Most of them having the Engraver's mark MB. )
(XXIII.

a Company sitting at a Table drinking, the Landlady
Standing in an undecent posture, telling the Score, with
these words above her: Macht selbst die zechg.

A man sitting in a Chair, putting on his Stocking, with his
privy parts in Sight, a Cat leaping at them, and a Girl
behind a Curtain, with this Inscription:
Cauda vah! dependet, cave, Catus prendet.

A shepherd & shepherdess embracing, near a Tree, with
this Motto: Pascua amoris, oscula oris.

A Woman sitting on a Bed, Cupid shooting an Arrow
at her, a Doctor feeling her Pulse wth one hand, and
in the other holding an Urinal, at which he looks: wth
this Motto: Vulva doles, Urina docet.

A Woman sitting, a Surgeon dressing her knee, with
this Motto: Charadoles pedibus? Sivevulmis altius?

A Gentleman riding from a Country Wench, who holds
the Reins, wth this Motto: Amasia! cur ingemescit ?
quia nesat dum venter crescit.

A Woman naked, recumbent, a youth, a Dog & monkey
near her, wth this motto: Vah Telotypia! Canis cum simia.

Bethsheba entering the Bath, King David on the
battlements of his Palace playing on the Harp, with
this Motto: Sic videre, facit dolere.

A naked Woman sitting w th her Legs in a Bath, two
male figures standing wi thin Rails looking at her, with
this Motto: Kehrt die Augen abthralten, hier die keusheit
bad will halten.

A naked woman recumbent, Cupid standing near her,
and an old man prostrate before her, with this Motto:
Ah quam vills amor senilis.

Diana ? bathing, wth her nymphs round her, and Action ?
in a Huntsman's Dress, having Stag's horns on his head, looking
on: with this Motto: Fac lateas et tutus eris.
(XXIV.

A Woman holding a Fruit in her right hand, Cupid.
standing by, offering her a Dish of fruit, with this Motto:
Virginibus prodest, cui pondus inest.

Fortune flying from off a winged Globe, wch two Men
endeavouring to detain her by pulling two Cords pass'd
round her Waist, & this Motto: Ah Fortuna bona! me condona.

Cupid pointing an Ar row on a grinding Stone, an old
man setting by him with a blunt ar row in his hand, and
this Motto: Venite heus! hebetes, Jiwenes et Senes.

A drunken Conversation , with this Motto:
Implendo lagenam, evacuo crumenam.

A gaming Company , with this Motto:
Nimius Lusus pecuniæ abusus.

The Duke of Bavaria ? on horseback, wch a Staff in his hand,
& this motto: Max. lman. DG. V. Ba. TE. P. S. D. C. P. R. S. R. J.
ar. Te. L. L.

An army drove into a River by a conquering Enemy,
with this Motto at top: Descenderunt velut lapis Exod. 15. 5.
& at bottom: Victoria ad Tibiscum 11. Sept. 1697.

A Cast of the Coronation medal of Frid. 3. k. of Prussia.
His Bust supported by Pallas, & Plenty with her horn.
The Inscription at top: nec virtuti gloria deest.
and at Bottom: Frideric. III. D. G. Brand. Supr. Borussiœ
Prin. in Regem inauguratus D. 18. Jan: 1701.*..

Prussia, in ye form of a Queen sitting, wth an angel behind
sounding the Trump of Fame, wth this Motto at Top.
Restituit nomenque decusque. and at bottom:
Borussia felsie. Ob antiquiss. Venedorum Regnum Eestau=
ratum *. The Reverse of ye preceding?

The late Empr Joseph, when K. of ye Romans, wth his Queen, and
this inscription above: Nil viget quicquam simile aut secundum.
and at bottom: Josephus et Withelmia D Amalia D. G. Rom.
Rex et Regina *.
